Let $y_{1}=\phi(x)$ and $y_{2}=\psi(x)$ be solutions of the ODE $$y''-2xy'+(sinx^2)y=0$$ such that $\phi(0)=1,\phi'(0)=1$ and $\psi(0)=1,\psi'(0)=2$. Then the value of the Wronskian $W(\phi,\psi)$ at $x=1$ is $0$ $1$ $e$ $e^2$ The Wronskian of a set of solutions for a second order ODE has a formula of the form: $W[\phi,\psi](x) = Ce^{f(x)}$, where $C$ is a constant and $f(x)$ is a function. I know that at any point $x_0$ \begin{alignat*}{2}
W(x_{0}) &= \left|
\begin{matrix}
\phi(x_{0}) & \psi(x_{0}) \\
\phi^{\prime}(x_{0}) & \psi^{\prime}(x_{0}) \\
\end{matrix}
\right|
&= \phi(x_{0})\psi^{\prime}(x_{0}) - \psi(x_{0})\phi^{\prime}(x_{0})
\end{alignat*} but I am unable to find  $C$ and $f$. Please help. Thanks.
